SIMPLE: wake
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wake
<hw>Wake</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Originally, an open
space of water surrounded by ice, and then, the passage cut through ice
for a vessel, probably of Scand. origin; cf. Icel. <ets>v⟦oum⟧k</ets> a
hole, opening in ice, Sw. <ets>vak</ets>, Dan. <ets>vaage</ets>, perhaps
akin to E. <ets>humid</ets>.]</ety> <def>The track left by a vessel in
the water; by extension, any track; <as>as, the <ex>wake</ex> of an
army</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This effect followed immediately in the <qex>wake</qex> of his
earliest exertions.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several humbler persons . . . formed quite a procession in the
dusty <qex>wake</qex> of his chariot wheels.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wake
<hw>Wake</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Waked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Woke</conjf> (<?/); <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Waking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wacan</ets>, <ets>wacian</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>waka</ets>,
OS. <ets>wak<?/n</ets>, D. <ets>waken</ets>, G. <ets>wachen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wahh<?/n</ets>, Icel. <ets>vaka</ets>, Sw. <ets>vaken</ets>, Dan.
<ets>vaage</ets>, Goth. <ets>wakan</ets>, v. i., us<ets>wakjan</ets>, v.
t., Skr. <ets>v⟦amac⟧jay</ets> to rouse, to impel. <?/<?/<?/<?/. Cf.
<er>Vigil</er>, <er>Wait</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, <er>Watch</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be or to continue awake; to watch; not to
sleep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The father <qex>waketh</qex> for the daughter.</q>
<rj><qau>Ecclus. xlii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though wisdom <qex>wake</qex>, suspicion sleeps.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not think any time, <qex>waking</qex> or sleeping, without
being sensible of it.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sit up late festive purposes; to hold a night
revel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king doth <qex>wake</qex> to-night, and takes his rouse,⟦br⟧
Keeps wassail, and the swaggering upspring reels.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be excited or roused from sleep; to awake; to be
awakened; to cease to sleep; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He infallibly <qex>woke</qex> up at the sound of the concluding
doxology.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be exited or roused up; to be stirred up from a
dormant, torpid, or inactive state; to be active.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gentle airs due at their hour⟦br⟧
To fan the earth now <qex>waked</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>wake</qex>, my soul, to high desires.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wake
<hw>Wake</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rouse
from sleep; to awake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The angel . . . came again and <qex>waked</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Zech. iv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put in motion or action; to arouse; to
excite.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I shall <xex>waken</xex> all this company.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest fierce remembrance <qex>wake</qex> my sudden rage.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Even Richard's crusade <qex>woke</qex> little interest in his
island realm.</q> <rj><qau>J. R. Green.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bring to life again, as if from the sleep of
death; to reanimate; to revive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To second life⟦br⟧
<qex>Waked</qex> in the renovation of the just.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To watch, or sit up with, at night, as a dead
body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wake
<hw>Wake</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of waking, or
being awaked; also, the state of being awake.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Making such difference 'twixt <qex>wake</qex> and sleep.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Singing her flatteries to my morning <qex>wake</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of forbearing sleep, especially for solemn
or festive purposes; a vigil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warlike <qex>wakes</qex> continued all the night,⟦br⟧
And funeral games played at new returning light.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wood nymphs, decked with daises trim,⟦br⟧
Their merry <qex>wakes</qex> and pastimes keep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Ch. of Eng.)</fld>
<def>An annual parish festival formerly held in commemoration of the
dedication of a church. Originally, prayers were said on the evening
preceding, and hymns were sung during the night, in the church;
subsequently, these vigils were discontinued, and the day itself, often
with succeeding days, was occupied in rural pastimes and exercises,
attended by eating and drinking, often to excess.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great solemnities were made in all churches, and great fairs and
<qex>wakes</qex> throughout all England.</q> <rj><qau>Ld.
Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And every village smokes at <qex>wakes</qex> with lusty cheer.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The sitting up of persons with a dead body, often
attended with a degree of festivity, chiefly among the Irish.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Blithe as shepherd at a <xex>wake</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wake play</b></col>, <cd>the ceremonies and pastimes
connected with a wake. See <er>Wake</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3 <sd>(b)</sd>,
above.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wakeful</ent>⟦br⟧
